[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] In mathematics, an **integral domain** is a nonzero commutative ring in which the product of any two nonzero elements is nonzero.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] In an integral domain, every nonzero element *a* has the cancellation property, that is, if *a* ≠ 0, *ab* = *ac* implies *b* = *c*.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] Integral domains are generalizations of the ring of integers and provide a setting that is useful for studying divisibility.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] "Integral domain" is defined almost universally as above, but there is some variation.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] This article follows the convention that rings have a multiplicative identity, generally denoted 1, but some authors do not follow this, by not requiring integral domains to have a multiplicative identity.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] Noncommutative integral domains are sometimes admitted.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] This article, however, follows the much more usual convention of reserving the term "integral domain" for the commutative case and using "domain" for the general case including noncommutative rings.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] Some sources, notably Lang, use the term **entire ring** for integral domain.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] An *integral domain* is a nonzero commutative ring in which the product of any two nonzero elements is nonzero.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] The following rings are *not* integral domains.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] In this section, *R* is an integral domain.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] Given elements *a* and *b* of *R*, one says that *a* *divides* *b*, or that *a* is a *divisor* of *b*, or that *b* is a *multiple* of *a*, if there exists an element *x* in *R* such that *ax* = *b*.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] The *units* of *R* are the elements that divide 1; these are precisely the invertible elements in *R*.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] If *a* divides *b* and *b* divides *a*, then *a* and *b* are **associated elements** or **associates**.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] Equivalently, *a* and *b* are associates if *a* = *ub* for some unit *u*.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] An *irreducible element* is a nonzero non-unit that cannot be written as a product of two non-units.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] A nonzero non-unit *p* is a *prime element* if, whenever *p* divides a product *ab*, then *p* divides *a* or *p* divides *b*.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] Equivalently, an element *p* is prime if and only if the principal ideal (*p*) is a nonzero prime ideal.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] Both notions of irreducible elements and prime elements generalize the ordinary definition of prime numbers in the ring $\mathbb {Z} ,$ if one considers as prime the negative primes.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] In a unique factorization domain (or more generally, a GCD domain), an irreducible element is a prime element.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] While unique factorization does not hold in $\mathbb {Z} \left[{\sqrt {-5}}\right]$ , there is unique factorization of ideals.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] The field of fractions *K* of an integral domain *R* is the set of fractions *a*/*b* with *a* and *b* in *R* and *b* ≠ 0 modulo an appropriate equivalence relation, equipped with the usual addition and multiplication operations.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] It is "the smallest field containing *R*" in the sense that there is an injective ring homomorphism *R* → *K* such that any injective ring homomorphism from *R* to a field factors through *K*.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] The field of fractions of the ring of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ is the field of rational numbers $\mathbb {Q} .$ The field of fractions of a field is isomorphic to the field itself.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] Integral domains are characterized by the condition that they are reduced (that is *x*2 = 0 implies *x* = 0) and irreducible (that is there is only one minimal prime ideal).
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] The former condition ensures that the nilradical of the ring is zero, so that the intersection of all the ring's minimal primes is zero.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] The latter condition is that the ring have only one minimal prime.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] It follows that the unique minimal prime ideal of a reduced and irreducible ring is the zero ideal, so such rings are integral domains.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] The converse is clear: an integral domain has no nonzero nilpotent elements, and the zero ideal is the unique minimal prime ideal.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] This translates, in algebraic geometry, into the fact that the coordinate ring of an affine algebraic set is an integral domain if and only if the algebraic set is an algebraic variety.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] More generally, a commutative ring is an integral domain if and only if its spectrum is an integral affine scheme.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] The characteristic of an integral domain is either 0 or a prime number.
[src:ring-theory/integral-domain] If *R* is an integral domain of prime characteristic *p*, then the Frobenius endomorphism *x* ↦ *x**p* is injective.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In mathematics, especially in the field of algebra, a **polynomial ring** or **polynomial algebra** is a ring formed from the set of polynomials in one or more **indeterminates** (traditionally also called variables) with coefficients in another ring, often a field.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Often, the term "polynomial ring" refers implicitly to the special case of a polynomial ring in one indeterminate over a field.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The importance of such polynomial rings relies on the high number of properties that they have in common with the ring of the integers.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Polynomial rings occur and are often fundamental in many parts of mathematics such as number theory, commutative algebra, and algebraic geometry.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In ring theory, many classes of rings, such as unique factorization domains, regular rings, group rings, rings of formal power series, Ore polynomials, graded rings, have been introduced for generalizing some properties of polynomial rings.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A closely related notion is that of the ring of polynomial functions on a vector space, and, more generally, ring of regular functions on an algebraic variety.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Let *K* be a field or (more generally) a commutative ring.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The **polynomial ring** in *X* over *K*, which is denoted *K*[*X*], can be defined in several equivalent ways.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] where m is a nonnegative integer, the **coefficients** *p*0, *p*1, ..., *p**m* of *p* are elements of *K*, and *X*, *X*2, …, are symbols called "powers" of *X* that follow the usual rules of exponents: *X*0 = 1, *X*1 = *X*, and $X^{k}\cdot X^{l}=X^{k+l}$ for any nonnegative integers *k* and *l*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The symbol *X* is called an indeterminate or variable.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] (The term of "variable" comes from the terminology of polynomial functions.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Two polynomials are equal when the corresponding coefficients of each *X**k* are equal.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] One can think of the ring *K*[*X*] as arising from *K* by adding one new element *X* that is external to *K*, commutes with all elements of *K*, and has no other specific properties.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This can be used for an equivalent definition of polynomial rings.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The polynomial ring in *X* over *K* is equipped with an addition, a multiplication and a scalar multiplication that make it a commutative algebra.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] These operations are defined according to the ordinary rules for manipulating algebraic expressions.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In these formulas, the polynomials *p* and *q* are extended by adding "dummy terms" with zero coefficients, so that all *p**i* and *q**i* that appear in the formulas are defined.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] It is straightforward to verify that these three operations satisfy the axioms of a commutative algebra over K.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Therefore, polynomial rings are also called *polynomial algebras*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In this case, *p*0 and X are considered as alternate notations for the sequences (*p*0, 0, 0, …) and (0, 1, 0, 0, …), respectively.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] be a nonzero polynomial with $p_{m}\neq 0$ .
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] It follows immediately that, if *K* is an integral domain, then so is *K*[*X*].
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] It follows also that, if *K* is an integral domain, a polynomial is a unit (that is, it has a multiplicative inverse) if and only if it is constant and is a unit in K.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Two polynomials are associated if either one is the product of the other by a unit.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Over a field, every nonzero polynomial is associated to a unique monic polynomial.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Given two polynomials, p and q, one says that p *divides* q, p is a *divisor* of q, or q is a multiple of p, if there is a polynomial r such that *q* = *pr*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A polynomial is irreducible if it is not the product of two non-constant polynomials, or equivalently, if its divisors are either constant polynomials or have the same degree.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Let K be a field or, more generally, a commutative ring, and R a ring containing K.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] For any polynomial P in *K*[*X*] and any element a in R, the substitution of X with a in P defines an element of *R*, which is denoted *P*(*a*).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This element is obtained by carrying on in R after the substitution the operations indicated by the expression of the polynomial.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This computation is called the **evaluation** of *P* at *a*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] (in the first example *R* = *K*, and in the second one *R* = *K*[*X*]).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] explaining why the sentences "Let P be a polynomial" and "Let *P*(*X*) be a polynomial" are equivalent.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The *polynomial function* defined by a polynomial P is the function from K into K that is defined by $x\mapsto P(x).$ If K is an infinite field, two different polynomials define different polynomial functions, but this property is false for finite fields.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] For example, if K is a field with q elements, then the polynomials 0 and *X**q* − *X* both define the zero function.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] For every *a* in *R*, the evaluation at a, that is, the map $P\mapsto P(a)$ defines an algebra homomorphism from *K*[*X*] to *R*, which is the unique homomorphism from *K*[*X*] to *R* that fixes K, and maps X to a.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] As for all universal properties, this defines the pair (*K*[*X*], *X*) up to a unique isomorphism, and can therefore be taken as a definition of *K*[*X*].
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The image of the map $P\mapsto P(a)$ , that is, the subset of R obtained by substituting a for X in elements of *K*[*X*], is denoted *K*[*a*] and called the adjunction of *a* to *K*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] If K is a field, the polynomial ring *K*[*X*] has many properties that are similar to those of the ring of integers $\mathbb {Z} .$ Most of these similarities result from the similarity between the long division of integers and the long division of polynomials.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Most of the properties of *K*[*X*] that are listed in this section do not remain true if K is not a field, or if one considers polynomials in several indeterminates.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Like for integers, the Euclidean division of polynomials has a property of uniqueness.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] That is, given two polynomials a and *b* ≠ 0 in *K*[*X*], there is a unique pair (*q*, *r*) of polynomials such that *a* = *bq* + *r*, and either *r* = 0 or deg(*r*) < deg(*b*).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] However, most other Euclidean domains (except integers) do not have any property of uniqueness for the division nor an easy algorithm (such as long division) for computing the Euclidean division.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The Euclidean division is the basis of the Euclidean algorithm for polynomials that computes a polynomial greatest common divisor of two polynomials.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Here, "greatest" means "having a maximal degree" or, equivalently, being maximal for the preorder defined by the degree.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Given a greatest common divisor of two polynomials, the other greatest common divisors are obtained by multiplication by a nonzero constant (that is, all greatest common divisors of a and b are associated).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In particular, two polynomials that are not both zero have a unique greatest common divisor that is monic (leading coefficient equal to 1).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The extended Euclidean algorithm allows computing (and proving) Bézout's identity.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In the case of *K*[*X*], it may be stated as follows.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] (For making this true in the limiting case where *m* = *d* or *n* = *d*, one has to define as negative the degree of the zero polynomial.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Moreover, the equality $\deg(a)=n-d$ can occur only if p and q are associated.) The uniqueness property is rather specific to *K*[*X*].
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In the case of the integers the same property is true, if degrees are replaced by absolute values, but, for having uniqueness, one must require *a* > 0.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] That is, if a divides bc, and is coprime with b, then a divides c.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Here, *coprime* means that the monic greatest common divisor is 1.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] *Proof:* By hypothesis and Bézout's identity, there are e, p, and q such that *ae* = *bc* and 1 = *ap* + *bq*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The unique factorization property results from Euclid's lemma.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In the case of integers, this is the fundamental theorem of arithmetic.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] If K is the field of complex numbers, the fundamental theorem of algebra asserts that a univariate polynomial is irreducible if and only if its degree is one.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In the case of polynomials with real or complex coefficients, this is the standard derivative.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The above formula defines the derivative of a polynomial even if the coefficients belong to a ring on which no notion of limit is defined.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The derivative makes the polynomial ring a differential algebra.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The existence of the derivative is one of the main properties of a polynomial ring that is not shared with integers, and makes some computations easier on a polynomial ring than on integers.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A polynomial with coefficients in a field or integral domain is *square-free* if it does not have a multiple root in the algebraically closed field containing its coefficients.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In particular, a polynomial of degree n with real or complex coefficients is square-free if it has n distinct complex roots.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Equivalently, a polynomial over a field is square-free if and only if the greatest common divisor of the polynomial and its derivative is 1.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A *square-free factorization* of a polynomial is an expression for that polynomial as a product of powers of pairwise relatively prime square-free factors.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Over the real numbers (or any other field of characteristic 0), such a factorization can be computed efficiently by Yun's algorithm.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Less efficient algorithms are known for square-free factorization of polynomials over finite fields.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Given a finite set of ordered pairs $(x_{j},y_{j})$ with entries in a field and distinct values $x_{j}$ , among the polynomials $f(x)$ that interpolate these points (so that $f(x_{j})=y_{j}$ for all j ), there is a unique polynomial of smallest degree.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This is the *Lagrange interpolation polynomial* $L(x)$ .
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] If there are k ordered pairs, the degree of $L(x)$ is at most $k-1$ .
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The polynomial $L(x)$ can be computed explicitly in terms of the input data $(x_{j},y_{j})$ .
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A *decomposition* of a polynomial is a way of expressing it as a composition of other polynomials of degree larger than 1.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A polynomial that cannot be decomposed is *indecomposable*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Except for factorization, all previous properties of *K*[*X*] are effective, since their proofs, as sketched above, are associated with algorithms for testing the property and computing the polynomials whose existence are asserted.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Moreover these algorithms are efficient, as their computational complexity is a quadratic function of the input size.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The situation is completely different for factorization: the proof of the unique factorization does not give any hint for a method for factorizing.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Already for the integers, there is no known algorithm running on a classical (non-quantum) computer for factorizing them in polynomial time.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This is the basis of the RSA cryptosystem, widely used for secure Internet communications.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In the case of *K*[*X*], the factors, and the methods for computing them, depend strongly on K.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Over the complex numbers, the irreducible factors (those that cannot be factorized further) are all of degree one, while, over the real numbers, there are irreducible polynomials of degree 2, and, over the rational numbers, there are irreducible polynomials of any degree.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The existence of a factorization algorithm depends also on the ground field.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In the case of the real or complex numbers, Abel–Ruffini theorem shows that the roots of some polynomials, and thus the irreducible factors, cannot be computed exactly.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Therefore, a factorization algorithm can compute only approximations of the factors.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Various algorithms have been designed for computing such approximations, see Root finding of polynomials.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] There is an example of a field *K* such that there exist exact algorithms for the arithmetic operations of *K*, but there cannot exist any algorithm for deciding whether a polynomial of the form $X^{p}-a$ is irreducible or is a product of polynomials of lower degree.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] On the other hand, over the rational numbers and over finite fields, the situation is better than for integer factorization, as there are factorization algorithms that have a polynomial complexity.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] They are implemented in most general purpose computer algebra systems.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] If *θ* is an element of an associative K-algebra *L*, the polynomial evaluation at *θ* is the unique algebra homomorphism *φ* from *K*[*X*] into *L* that maps *X* to *θ* and does not affect the elements of *K* itself (it is the identity map on *K*).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] It consists of *substituting* *X* with *θ* in every polynomial.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The image of this *evaluation homomorphism* is the subalgebra generated by θ, which is necessarily commutative.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] If *φ* is injective, the subalgebra generated by θ is isomorphic to *K*[*X*].
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In this case, this subalgebra is often denoted by *K*[*θ*].
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The notation ambiguity is generally harmless, because of the isomorphism.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] If the evaluation homomorphism is not injective, this means that its kernel is a nonzero ideal, consisting of all polynomials that become zero when X is substituted with θ.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This ideal consists of all multiples of some monic polynomial, that is called the **minimal polynomial** of θ.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The term *minimal* is motivated by the fact that its degree is minimal among the degrees of the elements of the ideal.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] There are two main cases where minimal polynomials are considered.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In field theory and number theory, an element θ of an extension field L of K is algebraic over K if it is a root of some polynomial with coefficients in K.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The minimal polynomial over K of θ is thus the monic polynomial of minimal degree that has θ as a root.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Because L is a field, this minimal polynomial is necessarily irreducible over K.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] For example, the minimal polynomial (over the reals as well as over the rationals) of the complex number i is $X^{2}+1$ .
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The cyclotomic polynomials are the minimal polynomials of the roots of unity.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In linear algebra, the *n*×*n* square matrices over K form an associative K-algebra of finite dimension (as a vector space).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Therefore the evaluation homomorphism cannot be injective, and every matrix has a minimal polynomial (not necessarily irreducible).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] By Cayley–Hamilton theorem, the evaluation homomorphism maps to zero the characteristic polynomial of a matrix.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] It follows that the minimal polynomial divides the characteristic polynomial, and therefore that the degree of the minimal polynomial is at most n.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In the case of *K*[*X*], the quotient ring by an ideal can be built, as in the general case, as a set of equivalence classes.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] However, as each equivalence class contains exactly one polynomial of minimal degree, another construction is often more convenient.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The ring $K[X]/(p)$ is a field if and only if p is an irreducible polynomial.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In fact, if p is irreducible, every nonzero polynomial q of lower degree is coprime with p, and Bézout's identity allows computing r and s such that *sp* + *qr* = 1; so, r is the multiplicative inverse of q modulo p.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Conversely, if p is reducible, then there exist polynomials a, b of degrees lower than deg(*p*) such that *ab* = *p* ; so a, b are nonzero zero divisors modulo p, and cannot be invertible.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] and that the image of X in $\mathbb {C}$ is denoted by i.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This construction of $\mathbb {C}$ illustrates the more general construction of quadratic algebras as quotient rings over a monic, quadratic polynomial.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Let *θ* be an algebraic element in a K-algebra A.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] By *algebraic*, one means that *θ* has a minimal polynomial p.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The first ring isomorphism theorem asserts that the substitution homomorphism induces an isomorphism of $K[X]/(p)$ onto the image *K*[*θ*] of the substitution homomorphism.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In particular, if A is a simple extension of K generated by *θ*, this allows identifying A and $K[X]/(p).$ This identification is widely used in algebraic number theory.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The structure theorem for finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain applies to *K*[*X*], when *K* is a field.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This means that every finitely generated module over *K*[*X*] may be decomposed into a direct sum of a free module and finitely many modules of the form $K[X]/\left\langle P^{k}\right\rangle$ , where *P* is an irreducible polynomial over *K* and *k* a positive integer.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] is a formal product of these indeterminates, possibly raised to a nonnegative power.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] As usual, exponents equal to one and factors with a zero exponent can be omitted.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The tuple of exponents *α* = (*α*1, …, *α**n*) is called the *multidegree* or *exponent vector* of the monomial.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] where the coefficients $p_{\alpha }$ are elements of K.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The *degree* of a nonzero polynomial is the maximum of the degrees of its monomials with nonzero coefficients.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The set of polynomials in $X_{1},\dots ,X_{n},$ denoted $K[X_{1},\dots ,X_{n}],$ is thus a vector space (or a free module, if K is a ring) that has the monomials as a basis.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] If the ring K is commutative, $K[X_{1},\dots ,X_{n}]$ is also a commutative ring.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] where $p_{\alpha }=0$ if $\alpha \not \in I,$ and $q_{\beta }=0$ if $\beta \not \in J.$ Moreover, if one has $p_{\alpha }+q_{\alpha }=0$ for some $\alpha \in I\cap J,$ the corresponding zero term is removed from the result.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] where $I+J$ is the set of the sums of one exponent vector in I and one other in J (usual sum of vectors).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In particular, the product of two monomials is a monomial whose exponent vector is the sum of the exponent vectors of the factors.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The verification of the axioms of an associative algebra is straightforward.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A **polynomial expression** is an expression built with scalars (elements of K), indeterminates, and the operators of addition, multiplication, and exponentiation to nonnegative integer powers.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The distinction between a polynomial expression and the polynomial that it represents is relatively recent, and mainly motivated by the rise of computer algebra, where, for example, the test whether two polynomial expressions represent the same polynomial may be a nontrivial computation.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] As it is the case for every universal property, this characterizes the pair $(K[X_{1},\dots ,X_{n}],(X_{1},\dots ,X_{n}))$ up to a unique isomorphism.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This may also be interpreted in terms of adjoint functors.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] More precisely, let SET and ALG be respectively the categories of sets and commutative K-algebras (here, and in the following, the morphisms are trivially defined).
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] There is a forgetful functor $\mathrm {F$ that maps algebras to their underlying sets.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] On the other hand, the map $X\mapsto K[X]$ defines a functor $\mathrm {POL$ in the other direction.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The universal property of the polynomial ring means that F and POL are adjoint functors.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This may be expressed also by saying that polynomial rings are **free commutative algebras**, since they are free objects in the category of commutative algebras.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Similarly, a polynomial ring with integer coefficients is the **free commutative ring** over its set of variables, since commutative rings and commutative algebras over the integers are the same thing.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] which results from the distributivity and associativity of ring operations.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In other words, a multivariate polynomial ring can be considered as a univariate polynomial over a smaller polynomial ring.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This is commonly used for proving properties of multivariate polynomial rings, by induction on the number of indeterminates.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The main such properties are listed below.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In this section, R is a commutative ring, K is a field, X denotes a single indeterminate, and, as usual, $\mathbb {Z}$ is the ring of integers.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Here is the list of the main ring properties that remain true when passing from R to *R*[*X*].
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Polynomial rings in several variables over a field are fundamental in invariant theory and algebraic geometry.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Some of their properties, such as those described above can be reduced to the case of a single indeterminate, but this is not always the case.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In particular, because of the geometric applications, many interesting properties must be invariant under affine or projective transformations of the indeterminates.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This often implies that one cannot select one of the indeterminates for a recurrence on the indeterminates.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Bézout's theorem, Hilbert's Nullstellensatz and Jacobian conjecture are among the most famous properties that are specific to multivariate polynomials over a field.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The Nullstellensatz (German for "zero-locus theorem") is a theorem, first proved by David Hilbert, which extends to the multivariate case some aspects of the fundamental theorem of algebra.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] It is foundational for algebraic geometry, as establishing a strong link between the algebraic properties of $K[X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}]$ and the geometric properties of algebraic varieties, that are (roughly speaking) set of points defined by implicit polynomial equations.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The Nullstellensatz, has three main versions, each being a corollary of any other.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] For the third version, the reader is referred to the main article on the Nullstellensatz.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The first version generalizes the fact that a nonzero univariate polynomial has a complex zero if and only if it is not a constant.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The statement is: *a set of polynomials S in $K[X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}]$ has a common zero in an algebraically closed field containing K, if and only if* 1 *does not belong to the ideal generated by S, that is, if* 1 *is not a linear combination of elements of S with polynomial coefficients*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Bézout's theorem may be viewed as a multivariate generalization of the version of the fundamental theorem of algebra that asserts that a univariate polynomial of degree n has n complex roots, if they are counted with their multiplicities.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] For stating the general case, and not considering "zero at infinity" as special zeros, it is convenient to work with homogeneous polynomials, and consider zeros in a projective space.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] In this context, a *projective zero* of a homogeneous polynomial $P(X_{0},\ldots ,X_{n})$ is, up to a scaling, a (*n* + 1)-tuple $(x_{0},\ldots ,x_{n})$ of elements of K that is different from (0, …, 0), and such that $P(x_{0},\ldots ,x_{n})=0$ .
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Here, "up to a scaling" means that $(x_{0},\ldots ,x_{n})$ and $(\lambda x_{0},\ldots ,\lambda x_{n})$ are considered as the same zero for any nonzero $\lambda \in K.$ In other words, a zero is a set of homogeneous coordinates of a point in a projective space of dimension n.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Polynomial rings can be generalized in a great many ways, including polynomial rings with generalized exponents, power series rings, noncommutative polynomial rings, skew polynomial rings, and polynomial rigs.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] One slight generalization of polynomial rings is to allow for infinitely many indeterminates.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Each monomial still involves only a finite number of indeterminates (so that its degree remains finite), and each polynomial is a still a (finite) linear combination of monomials.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Thus, any individual polynomial involves only finitely many indeterminates, and any finite computation involving polynomials remains inside some subring of polynomials in finitely many indeterminates.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This generalization has the same property of usual polynomial rings, of being the free commutative algebra, the only difference is that it is a free object over an infinite set.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] One can also consider a strictly larger ring, by defining as a generalized polynomial an infinite (or finite) formal sum of monomials with a bounded degree.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This ring is larger than the usual polynomial ring, as it includes infinite sums of variables.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] However, it is smaller than the ring of power series in infinitely many variables.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Such a ring is used for constructing the ring of symmetric functions over an infinite set.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A simple generalization only changes the set from which the exponents on the variable are drawn.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The formulas for addition and multiplication make sense as long as one can add exponents: *X**i* ⋅ *X**j* = *X**i*+*j*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A set for which addition makes sense (is closed and associative) is called a monoid.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The set of functions from a monoid *N* to a ring *R* which are nonzero at only finitely many places can be given the structure of a ring known as *R*[*N*], the **monoid ring** of *N* with coefficients in *R*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The addition is defined component-wise, so that if *c* = *a* + *b*, then *c**n* = *a**n* + *b**n* for every *n* in *N*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The multiplication is defined as the Cauchy product, so that if *c* = *a* ⋅ *b*, then for each *n* in *N*, *c**n* is the sum of all *a**i**b**j* where *i*, *j* range over all pairs of elements of *N* which sum to *n*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] where the latter sum is taken over all *i*, *j* in *N* that sum to *n*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Some authors go so far as to take this monoid definition as the starting point, and regular single variable polynomials are the special case where *N* is the monoid of non-negative integers.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Polynomials in several variables simply take *N* to be the direct product of several copies of the monoid of non-negative integers.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Several interesting examples of rings and groups are formed by taking *N* to be the additive monoid of non-negative rational numbers.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Power series generalize the choice of exponent in a different direction by allowing infinitely many nonzero terms.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This requires various hypotheses on the monoid *N* used for the exponents, to ensure that the sums in the Cauchy product are finite sums.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Alternatively, a topology can be placed on the ring, and then one restricts to convergent infinite sums.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] For the standard choice of *N*, the non-negative integers, there is no trouble, and the ring of formal power series is defined as the set of functions from *N* to a ring *R* with addition component-wise, and multiplication given by the Cauchy product.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The ring of power series can also be seen as the ring completion of the polynomial ring with respect to the ideal generated by x.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] For polynomial rings of more than one variable, the products *X*⋅*Y* and *Y*⋅*X* are simply defined to be equal.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A more general notion of polynomial ring is obtained when the distinction between these two formal products is maintained.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Formally, the polynomial ring in *n* noncommuting variables with coefficients in the ring *R* is the monoid ring *R*[*N*], where the monoid *N* is the free monoid on *n* letters, also known as the set of all strings over an alphabet of *n* symbols, with multiplication given by concatenation.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Neither the coefficients nor the variables need commute amongst themselves, but the coefficients and variables commute with each other.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Other generalizations of polynomials are differential and skew-polynomial rings.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] A **differential polynomial ring** is a ring of differential operators formed from a ring *R* and a derivation *δ* of *R* into *R*.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This derivation operates on *R*, and will be denoted *X*, when viewed as an operator.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The elements of *R* also operate on *R* by multiplication.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The composition of operators is denoted as the usual multiplication.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] This relation may be extended to define a skew multiplication between two polynomials in *X* with coefficients in *R*, which make them a noncommutative ring.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The standard example, called a Weyl algebra, takes *R* to be a (usual) polynomial ring *k*[*Y* ], and *δ* to be the standard polynomial derivative ${\tfrac {\partial }{\partial Y}}$ .
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Taking *a* = *Y* in the above relation, one gets the canonical commutation relation, *X*⋅*Y* − *Y*⋅*X* = 1.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] Extending this relation by associativity and distributivity allows explicitly constructing the Weyl algebra.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The **skew-polynomial ring** is defined similarly for a ring *R* and a ring endomorphism *f* of *R*, by extending the multiplication from the relation *X*⋅*r* = *f*(*r*)⋅*X* to produce an associative multiplication that distributes over the standard addition.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] More generally, given a homomorphism *F* from the monoid **N** of the positive integers into the endomorphism ring of *R*, the formula *X**n*⋅*r* = *F*(*n*)(*r*)⋅*X**n* allows constructing a skew-polynomial ring.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] (Lam 2001, §1,ex 1.11) Skew polynomial rings are closely related to crossed product algebras.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] The definition of a polynomial ring can be generalised by relaxing the requirement that the algebraic structure *R* be a field or a ring to the requirement that *R* only be a semifield or rig; the resulting polynomial structure/extension *R*[*X*] is a **polynomial rig**.
[src:ring-theory/polynomial-ring] For example, the set of all multivariate polynomials with natural number coefficients is a polynomial rig.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **ring** is an algebraic structure consisting of a set with two binary operations typically called *addition* and *multiplication* and denoted like addition and multiplication of integers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] They work similarly to integer addition and multiplication, except that multiplication in a ring does not need to be commutative.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Ring elements may be numbers such as integers or complex numbers, but they may also be non-numerical objects such as polynomials, square matrices, functions, and power series.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] More formally, a ring is a set that is endowed with two binary operations (*addition* and *multiplication*) such that the ring is an abelian group with respect to addition.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The multiplication is associative, is distributive over the addition operation, and has a multiplicative identity element.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Some authors apply the term *ring* to a further generalization, often called a *rng*, that omits the requirement for a multiplicative identity, and instead call the structure defined above a *ring with identity*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A *commutative ring* is a ring with a commutative multiplication.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] This property has profound implications on ring properties.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Commutative algebra, the theory of commutative rings, is a major branch of ring theory.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Its development has been greatly influenced by problems and ideas of algebraic number theory and algebraic geometry.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In turn, commutative algebra is a fundamental tool in these branches of mathematics.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Examples of commutative rings include every field (such as the real or complex numbers), the integers, the polynomials in one or several variables with coefficients in another ring, the coordinate ring of an affine algebraic variety, and the ring of integers of a number field.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Examples of noncommutative rings include the ring of *n* × *n* real square matrices with *n* ≥ 2, group rings in representation theory, operator algebras in functional analysis, rings of differential operators, and cohomology rings in topology.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The conceptualization of rings spanned the 1870s to the 1920s, with key contributions by Richard Dedekind, David Hilbert, Abraham Fraenkel, and Emmy Noether.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Rings were first formalized as a generalization of Dedekind domains that occur in number theory, and of polynomial rings and rings of invariants that occur in algebraic geometry and invariant theory.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] They later proved useful in other branches of mathematics such as geometry and analysis.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In notation, the multiplication symbol · is often omitted, in which case *a* · *b* is written as *ab*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In the terminology of this article, a ring is defined to have a multiplicative identity, while a structure with the same axiomatic definition but without the requirement for a multiplicative identity is instead called a "rng" (IPA: /rʊŋ/) with a missing "i".
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For example, the set of even integers with the usual + and ⋅ is a rng, but not a ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] As explained in *§ History* below, many authors apply the term "ring" without requiring a multiplicative identity.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Although ring addition is commutative, ring multiplication is not required to be commutative: ab need not necessarily equal *ba*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Rings that also satisfy commutativity for multiplication (such as the ring of integers) are called *commutative rings*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Books on commutative algebra or algebraic geometry often adopt the convention that *ring* means *commutative ring*, to simplify terminology.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In a ring, multiplicative inverses are not required to exist.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A nonzero ring in which every nonzero element has a multiplicative inverse is called a division ring and a commutative division ring is called a field.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The additive group of a ring is the underlying set equipped with only the operation of addition.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Although the definition requires that the additive group be abelian, this can be inferred from the other ring axioms.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The proof makes use of the "1", and does not work in a rng.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Some authors use the term "ring" to refer to structures in which there is no requirement for multiplication to be associative; see the nonassociative ring subsection below.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For these authors, every algebra is a "ring".
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The axioms of a ring are modeled on familiar properties of addition and multiplication of integers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] With the operations of matrix addition and matrix multiplication, $\operatorname {M} _{2}(F)$ satisfies the above ring axioms.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The element $\left({\begin{smallmatrix}1&0\\0&1\end{smallmatrix}}\right)$ is the multiplicative identity of the ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] More generally, for any ring R, commutative or not, and any nonnegative integer n, the square *n* × *n* matrices with entries in R form a ring; see *Matrix ring*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The study of rings originated from the theory of polynomial rings and the theory of algebraic integers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In 1871, Richard Dedekind defined the concept of the ring of integers of a number field.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In this context, he introduced the terms "ideal" (inspired by Ernst Kummer's notion of ideal number) and "module" and studied their properties.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Dedekind did not use the term "ring" and did not define the concept of a ring in a general setting.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The term "Zahlring" (number ring) was coined by David Hilbert in 1892 and published in 1897.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] According to Harvey Cohn, Hilbert used the term for a ring that had the property of "circling directly back" to an element of itself (in the sense of an equivalence).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Specifically, in a ring of algebraic integers, all high powers of an algebraic integer can be written as an integral combination of a fixed set of lower powers, and thus the powers "cycle back".
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] and so on; in general, *a**n* is going to be an integral linear combination of 1, *a*, and *a*2.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The first axiomatic definition of a ring was given by Abraham Fraenkel in 1915, but his axioms were stricter than those in the modern definition.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For instance, he required every non-zero-divisor to have a multiplicative inverse.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In 1921, Emmy Noether gave a modern axiomatic definition of commutative rings (with and without 1) and developed the foundations of commutative ring theory in her paper *Idealtheorie in Ringbereichen*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Fraenkel applied the term "ring" to structures with axioms that included a multiplicative identity, whereas Noether applied it to structures that did not.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Most or all books on algebra up to around 1960 followed Noether's convention of not requiring a 1 for a "ring".
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Starting in the 1960s, it became increasingly common to see books including the existence of 1 in the definition of "ring", especially in advanced books by notable authors such as Artin, Bourbaki, Eisenbud, and Lang.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] There are also books published as late as 2022 that use the term without the requirement for a 1.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Likewise, the Encyclopedia of Mathematics does not require unit elements in rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In a research article, the authors often specify which definition of ring they use in the beginning of that article.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] They conclude that "in many, maybe most, branches of ring theory the requirement of the existence of a unity element is not sensible, and therefore unacceptable." Poonen makes the counterargument that the natural notion for rings would be the direct product rather than the direct sum.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] However, his main argument is that rings without a multiplicative identity are not totally associative, in the sense that they do not contain the product of any finite sequence of ring elements, including the empty sequence.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For each nonnegative integer n, given a sequence ⁠ $(a_{1},\dots ,a_{n})$ ⁠ of n elements of R, one can define the product ⁠ $\textstyle P_{n}=\prod _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}$ ⁠ recursively: let *P*0 = 1 and let *P**m* = *P**m*−1*a**m* for 1 ≤ *m* ≤ *n*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] As a special case, one can define nonnegative integer powers of an element a of a ring: *a*0 = 1 and *a**n* = *a**n*−1*a* for *n* ≥ 1.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A left zero divisor of a ring R is an element a in the ring such that there exists a nonzero element b of R such that *ab* = 0.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A right zero divisor is defined similarly.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A nilpotent element is an element a such that *an* = 0 for some *n* > 0.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] One example of a nilpotent element is a nilpotent matrix.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A nilpotent element in a nonzero ring is necessarily a zero divisor.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] An idempotent e is an element such that *e*2 = *e*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] One example of an idempotent element is a projection in linear algebra.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A unit is an element a having a multiplicative inverse; in this case the inverse is unique, and is denoted by *a*–1.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The set of units of a ring is a group under ring multiplication; this group is denoted by *R*× or *R** or *U*(*R*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For example, if R is the ring of all square matrices of size n over a field, then *R*× consists of the set of all invertible matrices of size n, and is called the general linear group.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For example, the ring ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ of integers is a subring of the field of real numbers and also a subring of the ring of polynomials ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} [X]$ ⁠ (in both cases, ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ contains 1, which is the multiplicative identity of the larger rings).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, the subset of even integers ⁠ $2\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ does not contain the identity element 1 and thus does not qualify as a subring of ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} ;$ ⁠ one could call ⁠ $2\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ a subrng, however.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] An intersection of subrings is a subring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Given a subset E of R, the smallest subring of R containing E is the intersection of all subrings of R containing E, and it is called *the subring generated by E*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For a ring R, the smallest subring of R is called the *characteristic subring* of R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] It can be generated through addition of copies of 1 and −1.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] It is possible that *n* · 1 = 1 + 1 + ... + 1 (n times) can be zero.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If n is the smallest positive integer such that this occurs, then n is called the *characteristic* of R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In some rings, *n* · 1 is never zero for any positive integer n, and those rings are said to have *characteristic zero*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Given a ring R, let Z(*R*) denote the set of all elements x in R such that x commutes with every element in R: *xy* = *yx* for any y in R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Then Z(*R*) is a subring of R, called the center of R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] More generally, given a subset X of R, let S be the set of all elements in R that commute with every element in X.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Then S is a subring of R, called the centralizer (or commutant) of X.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The center is the centralizer of the entire ring R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Elements or subsets of the center are said to be *central* in R; they (each individually) generate a subring of the center.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A **left ideal** of R is a nonempty subset I of R such that for any x, y in I and r in R, the elements *x* + *y* and rx are in I.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Similarly, a **right ideal** is a subset I such that *IR* ⊆ *I*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A subset I is said to be a **two-sided ideal** or simply **ideal** if it is both a left ideal and right ideal.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A one-sided or two-sided ideal is then an additive subgroup of R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If E is a subset of R, then *RE* is a left ideal, called the left ideal generated by E; it is the smallest left ideal containing E.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Similarly, one can consider the right ideal or the two-sided ideal generated by a subset of R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If x is in R, then *Rx* is a left ideal, and *xR* is a right ideal; they are called the principal left ideal and right ideal generated by x.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The principal ideal *RxR* is written as (*x*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For example, the set of all positive and negative multiples of 2 along with 0 form an ideal of the integers, and this ideal is generated by the integer 2.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In fact, every ideal of the ring of integers is principal.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A ring is simple if it is nonzero and it has no proper nonzero two-sided ideals.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A commutative simple ring is precisely a field.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Rings are often studied with special conditions set upon their ideals.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For example, a ring in which there is no strictly increasing infinite chain of left ideals is called a left Noetherian ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A ring in which there is no strictly decreasing infinite chain of left ideals is called a left Artinian ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] It is a somewhat surprising fact that a left Artinian ring is left Noetherian (the Hopkins–Levitzki theorem).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The integers, however, form a Noetherian ring which is not Artinian.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For commutative rings, the ideals generalize the classical notion of divisibility and decomposition of an integer into prime numbers in algebra.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A proper ideal P of R is called a prime ideal if for any elements $x,y\in R$ we have that $xy\in P$ implies either $x\in P$ or $y\in P.$ Equivalently, P is prime if for any ideals *I*, *J* we have that *IJ* ⊆ *P* implies either *I* ⊆ *P* or *J* ⊆ *P*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] This latter formulation illustrates the idea of ideals as generalizations of elements.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If one is working with rngs, then the third condition is dropped.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A ring homomorphism f is said to be an **isomorphism** if there exists an inverse homomorphism to f (that is, a ring homomorphism that is an inverse function), or equivalently if it is bijective.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Given a ring homomorphism *f* : *R* → *S*, the set of all elements mapped to 0 by f is called the kernel of f.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The image of f, on the other hand, is not always an ideal, but it is always a subring of S.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] To give a ring homomorphism from a commutative ring R to a ring A with image contained in the center of A is the same as to give a structure of an algebra over R to A (which in particular gives a structure of an A-module).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The notion of quotient ring is analogous to the notion of a quotient group.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The ring *R* / *I* is also called a **factor ring**.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] As with a quotient group, there is a canonical homomorphism *p* : *R* → *R* / *I*, given by *x* ↦ *x* + *I*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For any ring homomorphism *f* : *R* → *S*, invoking the universal property with *I* = ker *f* produces a homomorphism ${\overline {f}}:R/\ker f\to S$ that gives an isomorphism from *R* / ker *f* to the image of f.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The concept of a *module over a ring* generalizes the concept of a vector space (over a field) by generalizing from multiplication of vectors with elements of a field (scalar multiplication) to multiplication with elements of a ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] More precisely, given a ring R, an R-module M is an abelian group equipped with an operation *R* × *M* → *M* (associating an element of M to every pair of an element of R and an element of M) that satisfies certain axioms.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] This operation is commonly denoted by juxtaposition and called multiplication.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] When the ring is noncommutative these axioms define *left modules*; *right modules* are defined similarly by writing xa instead of ax.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] This is not only a change of notation, as the last axiom of right modules (that is *x*(*ab*) = (*xa*)*b*) becomes (*ab*)*x* = *b*(*ax*), if left multiplication (by ring elements) is used for a right module.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Basic examples of modules are ideals, including the ring itself.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Although similarly defined, the theory of modules is much more complicated than that of vector space, mainly, because, unlike vector spaces, modules are not characterized (up to an isomorphism) by a single invariant (the dimension of a vector space).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In particular, not all modules have a basis.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The axioms of modules imply that (−1)*x* = −*x*, where the first minus denotes the additive inverse in the ring and the second minus the additive inverse in the module.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Using this and denoting repeated addition by a multiplication by a positive integer allows identifying abelian groups with modules over the ring of integers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Any ring homomorphism induces a structure of a module: if *f* : *R* → *S* is a ring homomorphism, then S is a left module over R by the multiplication: *rs* = *f*(*r*)*s*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If R is commutative or if *f*(*R*) is contained in the center of S, the ring S is called a R-algebra.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In particular, every ring is an algebra over the integers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The ring *R* × *S* with the above operations of addition and multiplication and the multiplicative identity (1, 1) is called the **direct product** of R with S.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The same construction also works for an arbitrary family of rings: if Ri are rings indexed by a set I, then ${\textstyle \prod _{i\in I}R_{i}}$ is a ring with componentwise addition and multiplication.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A "finite" direct product may also be viewed as a direct sum of ideals.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Namely, let $R_{i},1\leq i\leq n$ be rings, ${\textstyle R_{i}\to R=\prod R_{i}}$ the inclusions with the images ${\mathfrak {a}}_{i}$ (in particular ${\mathfrak {a}}_{i}$ are rings though not subrings).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Clearly the direct sum of such ideals also defines a product of rings that is isomorphic to R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Equivalently, the above can be done through central idempotents.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Assume that R has the above decomposition.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Then we can write $1=e_{1}+\cdots +e_{n},\quad e_{i}\in {\mathfrak {a}}_{i}.$ By the conditions on ${\mathfrak {a}}_{i},$ one has that ei are central idempotents and *eiej* = 0, *i* ≠ *j* (orthogonal).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Again, one can reverse the construction.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Namely, if one is given a partition of 1 in orthogonal central idempotents, then let ${\mathfrak {a}}_{i}=Re_{i},$ which are two-sided ideals.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If each ei is not a sum of orthogonal central idempotents, then their direct sum is isomorphic to R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] An important application of an infinite direct product is the construction of a projective limit of rings (see below).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Another application is a restricted product of a family of rings (cf. adele ring).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] forms a commutative ring with the usual addition and multiplication, containing R as a subring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] It is called the polynomial ring over R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] More generally, the set $R\left[t_{1},\ldots ,t_{n}\right]$ of all polynomials in variables $t_{1},\ldots ,t_{n}$ forms a commutative ring, containing $R\left[t_{i}\right]$ as subrings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If R is an integral domain, then *R*[*t*] is also an integral domain; its field of fractions is the field of rational functions.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If R is a Noetherian ring, then *R*[*t*] is a Noetherian ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If R is a unique factorization domain, then *R*[*t*] is a unique factorization domain.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Finally, R is a field if and only if *R*[*t*] is a principal ideal domain.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Let $R\subseteq S$ be commutative rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Because of this, the polynomial f is often also denoted by *f*(*t*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The image of the map ⁠ $f\mapsto f(x)$ ⁠ is denoted by *R*[*x*]; it is the same thing as the subring of S generated by R and x.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In other words, it is the subalgebra of *k*[*t*] generated by *t*2 and *t*3.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Example: let f be a polynomial in one variable, that is, an element in a polynomial ring R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The result of substituting zero to h in (*f*(*x* + *h*) – *f*(*x*)) / *h* is *f'*(*x*), the derivative of f at x.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The substitution is a special case of the universal property of a polynomial ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The property states: given a ring homomorphism $\phi :R\to S$ and an element x in S there exists a unique ring homomorphism ${\overline {\phi }}:R[t]\to S$ such that ${\overline {\phi }}(t)=x$ and ${\overline {\phi }}$ restricts to ϕ.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For example, choosing a basis, a symmetric algebra satisfies the universal property and so is a polynomial ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] To give an example, let S be the ring of all functions from R to itself; the addition and the multiplication are those of functions.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Each r in R defines a constant function, giving rise to the homomorphism *R* → *S*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] (t maps to x) where ${\overline {f}}$ is the polynomial function defined by f.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The resulting map is injective if and only if R is infinite.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Given a non-constant monic polynomial f in *R*[*t*], there exists a ring S containing R such that f is a product of linear factors in *S*[*t*].
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The Hilbert's Nullstellensatz (theorem of zeros) states that there is a natural one-to-one correspondence between the set of all prime ideals in $k\left[t_{1},\ldots ,t_{n}\right]$ and the set of closed subvarieties of kn.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In particular, many local problems in algebraic geometry may be attacked through the study of the generators of an ideal in a polynomial ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] There are some other related constructions.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] together with multiplication and addition that mimic those for convergent series.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A formal power series ring does not have the universal property of a polynomial ring; a series may not converge after a substitution.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The important advantage of a formal power series ring over a polynomial ring is that it is local (in fact, complete).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Let R be a ring (not necessarily commutative).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The set of all square matrices of size n with entries in R forms a ring with the entry-wise addition and the usual matrix multiplication.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] It is called the matrix ring and is denoted by M*n*(*R*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Given a right R-module U, the set of all R-linear maps from U to itself forms a ring with addition that is of function and multiplication that is of composition of functions; it is called the endomorphism ring of U and is denoted by End*R*(*U*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Schur's lemma says that if U is a simple right R-module, then End*R*(*U*) is a division ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The Artin–Wedderburn theorem states any semisimple ring (cf. below) is of this form.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A ring R and the matrix ring M*n*(*R*) over it are Morita equivalent: the category of right modules of R is equivalent to the category of right modules over M*n*(*R*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In particular, two-sided ideals in R correspond in one-to-one to two-sided ideals in M*n*(*R*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Let Ri be a sequence of rings such that Ri is a subring of *R**i* + 1 for all i.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Then the union (or filtered colimit) of Ri is the ring $\varinjlim R_{i}$ defined as follows: it is the disjoint union of all Ri's modulo the equivalence relation *x* ~ *y* if and only if *x* = *y* in Ri for sufficiently large i.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Any ring is the filtered colimit (union) of its finitely generated subrings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A projective limit (or a filtered limit) of rings is defined as follows.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Suppose we are given a family of rings *R**i*, *i* running over positive integers, say, and ring homomorphisms *R**j* → *R**i*, *j* ≥ *i* such that *R**i* → *R**i* are all the identities and *R**k* → *R**j* → *R**i* is *R**k* → *R**i* whenever *k* ≥ *j* ≥ *i*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Then $\varprojlim R_{i}$ is the subring of $\textstyle \prod R_{i}$ consisting of (*x**n*) such that *x**j* maps to *x**i* under *R**j* → *R**i*, *j* ≥ *i*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] For an example of a projective limit, see *§ Completion*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The localization generalizes the construction of the field of fractions of an integral domain to an arbitrary ring and modules.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The localization is frequently applied to a commutative ring R with respect to the complement of a prime ideal (or a union of prime ideals) in R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In that case $S=R-{\mathfrak {p}},$ one often writes $R_{\mathfrak {p}}$ for $R\left[S^{-1}\right].$ $R_{\mathfrak {p}}$ is then a local ring with the maximal ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}R_{\mathfrak {p}}.$ This is the reason for the terminology "localization".
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The field of fractions of an integral domain R is the localization of R at the prime ideal zero.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] In category theory, a localization of a category amounts to making some morphisms isomorphisms.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] An element in a commutative ring R may be thought of as an endomorphism of any R-module.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Thus, categorically, a localization of R with respect to a subset S of R is a functor from the category of R-modules to itself that sends elements of S viewed as endomorphisms to automorphisms and is universal with respect to this property.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Let R be a commutative ring, and let I be an ideal of R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The **completion** of R at I is the projective limit ${\hat {R}}=\varprojlim R/I^{n};$ it is a commutative ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The canonical homomorphisms from R to the quotients $R/I^{n}$ induce a homomorphism $R\to {\hat {R}}.$ The latter homomorphism is injective if R is a Noetherian integral domain and I is a proper ideal, or if R is a Noetherian local ring with maximal ideal I, by Krull's intersection theorem.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The construction is especially useful when I is a maximal ideal.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] It defines a distance function on ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠ and the completion of ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠ as a metric space is denoted by ⁠ $\mathbb {Q} _{p}.$ ⁠ It is again a field since the field operations extend to the completion.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A complete ring has much simpler structure than a commutative ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] This owns to the Cohen structure theorem, which says, roughly, that a complete local ring tends to look like a formal power series ring or a quotient of it.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, the interaction between the integral closure and completion has been among the most important aspects that distinguish modern commutative ring theory from the classical one developed by the likes of Noether.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Pathological examples found by Nagata led to the reexamination of the roles of Noetherian rings and motivated, among other things, the definition of excellent ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] The most general way to construct a ring is by specifying generators and relations.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Let F be a free ring (that is, free algebra over the integers) with the set X of symbols, that is, F consists of polynomials with integral coefficients in noncommuting variables that are elements of X.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] A free ring satisfies the universal property: any function from the set X to a ring R factors through F so that *F* → *R* is the unique ring homomorphism.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Just as in the group case, every ring can be represented as a quotient of a free ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Now, we can impose relations among symbols in X by taking a quotient.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Explicitly, if E is a subset of F, then the quotient ring of F by the ideal generated by E is called the ring with generators X and relations E.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] If we used a ring, say, A as a base ring instead of ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} ,$ ⁠ then the resulting ring will be over A.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p01] Let *A*, *B* be algebras over a commutative ring R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A nonzero ring with no nonzero zero-divisors is called a domain.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A commutative domain is called an integral domain.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The most important integral domains are principal ideal domains, PIDs for short, and fields.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A principal ideal domain is an integral domain in which every ideal is principal.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Among theorems concerning a PID, the most important one is the structure theorem for finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The theorem may be illustrated by the following application to linear algebra.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Let V be a finite-dimensional vector space over a field k and *f* : *V* → *V* a linear map with minimal polynomial q.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Thus, if, say, k is algebraically closed, then all pi's are of the form *t* – *λi* and the above decomposition corresponds to the Jordan canonical form of f.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In algebraic geometry, UFDs arise because of smoothness.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] More precisely, a point in a variety (over a perfect field) is smooth if the local ring at the point is a regular local ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A division ring is a ring such that every non-zero element is a unit.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A prominent example of a division ring that is not a field is the ring of quaternions.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Any centralizer in a division ring is also a division ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In particular, the center of a division ring is a field.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] It turned out that every *finite* domain (in particular finite division ring) is a field; in particular commutative (the Wedderburn's little theorem).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Every module over a division ring is a free module (has a basis); consequently, much of linear algebra can be carried out over a division ring instead of a field.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The study of conjugacy classes figures prominently in the classical theory of division rings; see, for example, the Cartan–Brauer–Hua theorem.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Dickson, is a generalization of a quaternion algebra.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A *semisimple module* is a direct sum of simple modules.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A *semisimple ring* is a ring that is semisimple as a left module (or right module) over itself.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The Weyl algebra over a field is a simple ring, but it is not semisimple.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The same holds for a ring of differential operators in many variables.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Any module over a semisimple ring is semisimple.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Semisimplicity is closely related to separability.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A unital associative algebra A over a field k is said to be separable if the base extension $A\otimes _{k}F$ is semisimple for every field extension *F* / *k*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] For a field k, a k-algebra is central if its center is k and is simple if it is a simple ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Since the center of a simple k-algebra is a field, any simple k-algebra is a central simple algebra over its center.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In this section, a central simple algebra is assumed to have finite dimension.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Also, we mostly fix the base field; thus, an algebra refers to a k-algebra.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The matrix ring of size n over a ring R will be denoted by *R**n*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The Skolem–Noether theorem states any automorphism of a central simple algebra is inner.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Two central simple algebras A and B are said to be *similar* if there are integers n and m such that $A\otimes _{k}k_{n}\approx B\otimes _{k}k_{m}.$ Since $k_{n}\otimes _{k}k_{m}\simeq k_{nm},$ the similarity is an equivalence relation.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The similarity classes [*A*] with the multiplication $[A][B]=\left[A\otimes _{k}B\right]$ form an abelian group called the Brauer group of k and is denoted by Br(*k*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] By the Artin–Wedderburn theorem, a central simple algebra is the matrix ring of a division ring; thus, each similarity class is represented by a unique division ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] For example, Br(*k*) is trivial if k is a finite field or an algebraically closed field (more generally quasi-algebraically closed field; cf.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Tsen's theorem). $\operatorname {Br} (\mathbb {R} )$ has order 2 (a special case of the theorem of Frobenius).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Finally, if k is a nonarchimedean local field (for example, ⁠ $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ ⁠), then $\operatorname {Br} (k)=\mathbb {Q} /\mathbb {Z}$ through the invariant map.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Now, if F is a field extension of k, then the base extension $-\otimes _{k}F$ induces Br(*k*) → Br(*F*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Azumaya algebras generalize the notion of central simple algebras to a commutative local ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] If K is a field, a valuation v is a group homomorphism from the multiplicative group *K*∗ to a totally ordered abelian group G such that, for any *f*, *g* in K with *f* + *g* nonzero, *v*(*f* + *g*) ≥ min{*v*(*f*), *v*(*g*)}.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The valuation ring of v is the subring of K consisting of zero and all nonzero f such that *v*(*f*) ≥ 0.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A ring may be viewed as an abelian group (by using the addition operation), with extra structure: namely, ring multiplication.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In the same way, there are other mathematical objects which may be considered as rings with extra structure.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Many different kinds of mathematical objects can be fruitfully analyzed in terms of some associated ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] There are also homology groups $H_{i}(X,\mathbb {Z} )$ of a space, and indeed these were defined first, as a useful tool for distinguishing between certain pairs of topological spaces, like the spheres and tori, for which the methods of point-set topology are not well-suited.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Cohomology groups were later defined in terms of homology groups in a way which is roughly analogous to the dual of a vector space.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] To know each individual integral homology group is essentially the same as knowing each individual integral cohomology group, because of the universal coefficient theorem.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] However, the advantage of the cohomology groups is that there is a natural product, which is analogous to the observation that one can multiply pointwise a k-multilinear form and an l-multilinear form to get a (*k* + *l*)-multilinear form.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The ring structure in cohomology provides the foundation for characteristic classes of fiber bundles, intersection theory on manifolds and algebraic varieties, Schubert calculus and much more.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] To any group is associated its Burnside ring which uses a ring to describe the various ways the group can act on a finite set.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The Burnside ring's additive group is the free abelian group whose basis is the set of transitive actions of the group and whose addition is the disjoint union of the action.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Expressing an action in terms of the basis is decomposing an action into its transitive constituents.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The multiplication is easily expressed in terms of the representation ring: the multiplication in the Burnside ring is formed by writing the tensor product of two permutation modules as a permutation module.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The ring structure allows a formal way of subtracting one action from another.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Since the Burnside ring is contained as a finite index subring of the representation ring, one can pass easily from one to the other by extending the coefficients from integers to the rational numbers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] To any group ring or Hopf algebra is associated its representation ring or "Green ring".
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The representation ring's additive group is the free abelian group whose basis are the indecomposable modules and whose addition corresponds to the direct sum.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Expressing a module in terms of the basis is finding an indecomposable decomposition of the module.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The multiplication is the tensor product.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] When the algebra is semisimple, the representation ring is just the character ring from character theory, which is more or less the Grothendieck group given a ring structure.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] To any irreducible algebraic variety is associated its function field.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The points of an algebraic variety correspond to valuation rings contained in the function field and containing the coordinate ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The study of algebraic geometry makes heavy use of commutative algebra to study geometric concepts in terms of ring-theoretic properties.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Birational geometry studies maps between the subrings of the function field.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Every simplicial complex has an associated face ring, also called its Stanley–Reisner ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] This ring reflects many of the combinatorial properties of the simplicial complex, so it is of particular interest in algebraic combinatorics.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In particular, the algebraic geometry of the Stanley–Reisner ring was used to characterize the numbers of faces in each dimension of simplicial polytopes.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Every ring can be thought of as a monoid in **Ab**, the category of abelian groups (thought of as a monoidal category under the tensor product of ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠-modules).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] The monoid action of a ring R on an abelian group is simply an R-module.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Essentially, an R-module is a generalization of the notion of a vector space – where rather than a vector space over a field, one has a "vector space over a ring".
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Let (*A*, +) be an abelian group and let End(*A*) be its endomorphism ring (see above).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] where + as in *f*(*x*) + *g*(*x*) is addition in A, and function composition is denoted from right to left.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Therefore, associated to any abelian group, is a ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Furthermore, for every r in R, right (or left) multiplication by r gives rise to a morphism of (*R*, +), by right (or left) distributivity.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Consider those endomorphisms of A, that "factor through" right (or left) multiplication of R.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In other words, let End*R*(*A*) be the set of all morphisms m of A, having the property that *m*(*r* ⋅ *x*) = *r* ⋅ *m*(*x*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] It was seen that every r in R gives rise to a morphism of A: right multiplication by r.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] It is in fact true that this association of any element of R, to a morphism of A, as a function from R to End*R*(*A*), is an isomorphism of rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In this sense, therefore, any ring can be viewed as the endomorphism ring of some abelian X-group (by X-group, it is meant a group with X being its set of operators).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In essence, the most general form of a ring, is the endomorphism group of some abelian X-group.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Any ring can be seen as a preadditive category with a single object.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] It is therefore natural to consider arbitrary preadditive categories to be generalizations of rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] And indeed, many definitions and theorems originally given for rings can be translated to this more general context.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Additive functors between preadditive categories generalize the concept of ring homomorphism, and ideals in additive categories can be defined as sets of morphisms closed under addition and under composition with arbitrary morphisms.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Algebraists have defined structures more general than rings by weakening or dropping some of ring axioms.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A rng is the same as a ring, except that the existence of a multiplicative identity is not assumed.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A nonassociative ring is an algebraic structure that satisfies all of the ring axioms except the associative property and the existence of a multiplicative identity.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] There exists some structure theory for such algebras that generalizes the analogous results for Lie algebras and associative algebras.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] A semiring (sometimes *rig*) is obtained by weakening the assumption that (*R*, +) is an abelian group to the assumption that (*R*, +) is a commutative monoid, and adding the axiom that 0 ⋅ *a* = *a* ⋅ 0 = 0 for all *a* in R (since it no longer follows from the other axioms).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Let C be a category with finite products.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] Let pt denote a terminal object of C (an empty product).
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In algebraic geometry, a **ring scheme** over a base scheme S is a ring object in the category of S-schemes.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] One example is the ring scheme W*n* over ⁠ $\operatorname {Spec} \mathbb {Z}$ ⁠, which for any commutative ring A returns the ring W*n*(*A*) of p-isotypic Witt vectors of length n over A.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In algebraic topology, a ring spectrum is a spectrum X together with a multiplication $\mu :X\wedge X\to X$ and a unit map *S* → *X* from the sphere spectrum S, such that the ring axiom diagrams commute up to homotopy.
[src:ring-theory/ring-mathematics-p02] In practice, it is common to define a ring spectrum as a monoid object in a good category of spectra such as the category of symmetric spectra.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] In algebra, **ring theory** is the study of rings, algebraic structures in which addition and multiplication are defined and have similar properties to those operations defined for the integers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Commutative rings are much better understood than noncommutative ones.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Algebraic geometry and algebraic number theory, which provide many natural examples of commutative rings, have driven much of the development of commutative ring theory, which is now, under the name of *commutative algebra*, a major area of modern mathematics.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Because these three fields (algebraic geometry, algebraic number theory and commutative algebra) are so intimately connected it is usually difficult and meaningless to decide which field a particular result belongs to.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] For example, Hilbert's Nullstellensatz is a theorem which is fundamental for algebraic geometry, and is stated and proved in terms of commutative algebra.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Similarly, Fermat's Last Theorem is stated in terms of elementary arithmetic, which is a part of commutative algebra, but its proof involves deep results of both algebraic number theory and algebraic geometry.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Noncommutative rings are quite different in flavour, since more unusual behavior can arise.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] While the theory has developed in its own right, a fairly recent trend has sought to parallel the commutative development by building the theory of certain classes of noncommutative rings in a geometric fashion as if they were rings of functions on (non-existent) 'noncommutative spaces'.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] This trend started in the 1980s with the development of noncommutative geometry and with the discovery of quantum groups.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] It has led to a better understanding of noncommutative rings, especially noncommutative Noetherian rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] For the definitions of a ring and basic concepts and their properties, see *Ring (mathematics)*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The definitions of terms used throughout ring theory may be found in *Glossary of ring theory*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] A ring is called *commutative* if its multiplication is commutative.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Commutative rings resemble familiar number systems, and various definitions for commutative rings are designed to formalize properties of the integers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Commutative rings are also important in algebraic geometry.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] In commutative ring theory, numbers are often replaced by ideals, and the definition of the prime ideal tries to capture the essence of prime numbers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Integral domains, non-trivial commutative rings where no two non-zero elements multiply to give zero, generalize another property of the integers and serve as the proper realm to study divisibility.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Principal ideal domains are integral domains in which every ideal can be generated by a single element, another property shared by the integers.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Euclidean domains are integral domains in which the Euclidean algorithm can be carried out.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Important examples of commutative rings can be constructed as rings of polynomials and their factor rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Summary: Euclidean domain ⊂ principal ideal domain ⊂ unique factorization domain ⊂ integral domain ⊂ commutative ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Algebraic geometry is in many ways the mirror image of commutative algebra.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] This correspondence started with Hilbert's Nullstellensatz that establishes a one-to-one correspondence between the points of an algebraic variety, and the maximal ideals of its coordinate ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] This correspondence has been enlarged and systematized for translating (and proving) most geometrical properties of algebraic varieties into algebraic properties of associated commutative rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Alexander Grothendieck completed this by introducing schemes, a generalization of algebraic varieties, which may be built from any commutative ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] More precisely, the spectrum of a commutative ring is the space of its prime ideals equipped with Zariski topology, and augmented with a sheaf of rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] These objects are the "affine schemes" (generalization of affine varieties), and a general scheme is then obtained by "gluing together" (by purely algebraic methods) several such affine schemes, in analogy to the way of constructing a manifold by gluing together the charts of an atlas.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Noncommutative rings resemble rings of matrices in many respects.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Following the model of algebraic geometry, attempts have been made recently at defining noncommutative geometry based on noncommutative rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Noncommutative rings and associative algebras (rings that are also vector spaces) are often studied via their categories of modules.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] A module over a ring is an abelian group that the ring acts on as a ring of endomorphisms, very much akin to the way fields (integral domains in which every non-zero element is invertible) act on vector spaces.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Examples of noncommutative rings are given by rings of square matrices or more generally by rings of endomorphisms of abelian groups or modules, and by monoid rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Representation theory is a branch of mathematics that draws heavily on non-commutative rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] It studies abstract algebraic structures by *representing* their elements as linear transformations of vector spaces, and studies modules over these abstract algebraic structures.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] In essence, a representation makes an abstract algebraic object more concrete by describing its elements by matrices and the algebraic operations in terms of matrix addition and matrix multiplication, which is non-commutative.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The algebraic objects amenable to such a description include groups, associative algebras and Lie algebras.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The most prominent of these (and historically the first) is the representation theory of groups, in which elements of a group are represented by invertible matrices in such a way that the group operation is matrix multiplication.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] In this section, *R* denotes a commutative ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The Krull dimension of *R* is the supremum of the lengths *n* of all the chains of prime ideals ${\mathfrak {p}}_{0}\subsetneq {\mathfrak {p}}_{1}\subsetneq \cdots \subsetneq {\mathfrak {p}}_{n}$ .
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] It turns out that the polynomial ring $k[t_{1},\cdots ,t_{n}]$ over a field *k* has dimension *n*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Practically all noetherian rings that appear in applications are catenary.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] where $\operatorname {ht} {\mathfrak {p}}$ is the height of ${\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] If *R* is an integral domain that is a finitely generated *k*-algebra, then its dimension is the transcendence degree of its field of fractions over *k*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] If *S* is an integral extension of a commutative ring *R*, then *S* and *R* have the same dimension.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Closely related concepts are those of depth and global dimension.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] In general, if *R* is a noetherian local ring, then the depth of *R* is less than or equal to the dimension of *R*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] When the equality holds, *R* is called a Cohen–Macaulay ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] A regular local ring is an example of a Cohen–Macaulay ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] It is a theorem of Serre that *R* is a regular local ring if and only if it has finite global dimension and in that case the global dimension is the Krull dimension of *R*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The significance of this is that a global dimension is a homological notion.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Two rings *R*, *S* are said to be Morita equivalent if the category of left modules over *R* is equivalent to the category of left modules over *S*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] In fact, two commutative rings which are Morita equivalent must be isomorphic, so the notion does not add anything new to the category of commutative rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] However, commutative rings can be Morita equivalent to noncommutative rings, so Morita equivalence is coarser than isomorphism.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Morita equivalence is especially important in algebraic topology and functional analysis.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Let *R* be a commutative ring and $\mathbf {P} (R)$ the set of isomorphism classes of finitely generated projective modules over *R*; let also $\mathbf {P} _{n}(R)$ subsets consisting of those with constant rank *n*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] (The rank of a module *M* is the continuous function $\operatorname {Spec} R\to \mathbb {Z} ,\,{\mathfrak {p}}\mapsto \dim M\otimes _{R}k({\mathfrak {p}})$ .) $\mathbf {P} _{1}(R)$ is usually denoted by Pic(*R*).
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] It is an abelian group called the Picard group of *R*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] where $\operatorname {Cart} (R)$ is the set of fractional ideals of *R*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] If *R* is a regular domain (i.e., regular at any prime ideal), then Pic(R) is precisely the divisor class group of *R*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] For example, if *R* is a principal ideal domain, then Pic(*R*) vanishes.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] In algebraic number theory, *R* will be taken to be the ring of integers, which is Dedekind and thus regular.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] It follows that Pic(*R*) is a finite group (finiteness of class number) that measures the deviation of the ring of integers from being a PID.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] One can also consider the group completion of $\mathbf {P} (R)$ ; this results in a commutative ring K0(R).
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Note that K0(R) = K0(S) if two commutative rings *R*, *S* are Morita equivalent.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The structure of a noncommutative ring is more complicated than that of a commutative ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] For example, there exist simple rings that contain no non-trivial proper (two-sided) ideals, yet contain non-trivial proper left or right ideals.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Various invariants exist for commutative rings, whereas invariants of noncommutative rings are difficult to find.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] As an example, the nilradical of a ring, the set of all nilpotent elements, is not necessarily an ideal unless the ring is commutative.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Specifically, the set of all nilpotent elements in the ring of all *n* × *n* matrices over a division ring never forms an ideal, irrespective of the division ring chosen.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] There are, however, analogues of the nilradical defined for noncommutative rings, that coincide with the nilradical when commutativity is assumed.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The concept of the Jacobson radical of a ring; that is, the intersection of all right (left) annihilators of simple right (left) modules over a ring, is one example.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The fact that the Jacobson radical can be viewed as the intersection of all maximal right (left) ideals in the ring, shows how the internal structure of the ring is reflected by its modules.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] It is also a fact that the intersection of all maximal right ideals in a ring is the same as the intersection of all maximal left ideals in the ring, in the context of all rings; irrespective of whether the ring is commutative.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Noncommutative rings are an active area of research due to their ubiquity in mathematics.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] For instance, the ring of *n*-by-*n* matrices over a field is noncommutative despite its natural occurrence in geometry, physics and many parts of mathematics.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] More generally, endomorphism rings of abelian groups are rarely commutative, the simplest example being the endomorphism ring of the Klein four-group.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] One of the best-known strictly noncommutative ring is the quaternions.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] If *X* is an affine algebraic variety, then the set of all regular functions on *X* forms a ring called the coordinate ring of *X*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] For a projective variety, there is an analogous ring called the homogeneous coordinate ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Those rings are essentially the same things as varieties: they correspond in essentially a unique way.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] This may be seen via either Hilbert's Nullstellensatz or scheme-theoretic constructions (i.e., Spec and Proj).
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] A basic (and perhaps the most fundamental) question in the classical invariant theory is to find and study polynomials in the polynomial ring $k[V]$ that are invariant under the action of a finite group (or more generally reductive) *G* on *V*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The main example is the ring of symmetric polynomials: symmetric polynomials are polynomials that are invariant under permutation of variable.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The fundamental theorem of symmetric polynomials states that this ring is $R[\sigma _{1},\ldots ,\sigma _{n}]$ where $\sigma _{i}$ are elementary symmetric polynomials.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Commutative ring theory originated in algebraic number theory, algebraic geometry, and invariant theory.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Central to the development of these subjects were the rings of integers in algebraic number fields and algebraic function fields, and the rings of polynomials in two or more variables.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Noncommutative ring theory began with attempts to extend the complex numbers to various hypercomplex number systems.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The genesis of the theories of commutative and noncommutative rings dates back to the early 19th century, while their maturity was achieved only in the third decade of the 20th century.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] More precisely, William Rowan Hamilton put forth the quaternions and biquaternions; James Cockle presented tessarines and coquaternions; and William Kingdon Clifford was an enthusiast of split-biquaternions, which he called *algebraic motors*.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] These noncommutative algebras, and the non-associative Lie algebras, were studied within universal algebra before the subject was divided into particular mathematical structure types.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] One sign of re-organization was the use of direct sums to describe algebraic structure.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The various hypercomplex numbers were identified with matrix rings by Joseph Wedderburn (1908) and Emil Artin (1928).
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Wedderburn's structure theorems were formulated for finite-dimensional algebras over a field while Artin generalized them to Artinian rings.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] In 1920, Emmy Noether, in collaboration with W.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Schmeidler, published a paper about the theory of ideals in which they defined left and right ideals in a ring.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] The following year she published a landmark paper called *Idealtheorie in Ringbereichen*, analyzing ascending chain conditions with regard to (mathematical) ideals.
[src:ring-theory/ring-theory] Noted algebraist Irving Kaplansky called this work "revolutionary"; the publication gave rise to the term "Noetherian ring", and several other mathematical objects being called *Noetherian*.
